The state of Michigan is located in the Great Lakes region of the United States and has a distinctive shape that resembles a mitten. Michigan is made up of two peninsulas, the Upper Peninsula and the Lower Peninsula, which are separated by the Straits of Mackinac.

The Lower Peninsula is shaped like a mitten, with the Thumb region extending out to the east. It is bordered by Lake Michigan to the west, Lake Huron to the northeast, and Lake Erie to the southeast. The state capital, Lansing, is located near the center of the Lower Peninsula.

The Upper Peninsula is much less populated than the Lower Peninsula and is connected to it by the Mackinac Bridge. It is located to the north of the Lower Peninsula and is bordered by Lake Superior to the north and Lake Michigan to the west.

Overall, Michigan is a diverse state with a mix of urban and rural areas, as well as a variety of natural landscapes, including forests, lakes, and sandy beaches.